In [32]:
# categorical features vs matrix of numeric features 

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ https://github.com/mwaskom/seaborn/issues/915#issuecomment-595414614"""
    """he has solved the issue with simple trick"""
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 20]);
a = sb.PairGrid(data = sub_df, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], x_vars = ['Term', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'EmploymentStatus','BorrowerState'], size = 9, aspect = 1.5)

a.map(boxgrid);
plt.xticks(rotation=40);

(Employed, self-employed and full time) have more monthly income and loan amount #than(part-time, retired and not employed borrowers).

some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The borrower APR is negatively associated with loan_original_amount, the higher the loan amount, the higher the APR.

The Prosper rating also has a high effect on the APR, with the better rating this effect decreases.

at different size of the loan amount, the APR has a large range ,(in the higher loan it becomes small)

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

loan_original_amount is positively correlated with the stated_monthly_income, I think it's obvious since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money. It also shows that borrowers with better rating also have larger monthly income and loan amount. There is a (relation) interaction between prosper rating and term. there are more 60 month loans on B and C ratings. There is only 36 months loans for HR rating borrowers.

In [37]:
ni=sb.FacetGrid(data=sub_df, aspect=1.2, col='ProsperRating (Alpha)', col_wrap=4)
ni.map(sb.regplot, x = sub_df['LoanOriginalAmount'], y = sub_df['BorrowerAPR'], x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1}).add_legend();

The loan amount possitively increases with better rating. The APR decreases with better rating.

so, the relationship between APR and loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper_ratings are increased from HR to A or better.

it's a defence mechanism,as people with A or AA ratings borrow more money, increasing APR could prevent them borrow even more and maximize the profit. on the other hand people with lower ratings tend to borrow less money, decreasing APR could encourage them to borrow more.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

by looking at the impact of the Prosper_rating,I extended my investigation of APR VS loan_amount .

The multivariate exploration showed us the relationship between APR and loan_amount.

then,I've explored the rating and term_effects features on loan amount and I've found with better Prosper rating, the loan amount of all three terms increases, the increase of loan_amount between terms also becomes larger.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features¶

APR and loan amount is negatively correlated when the Prosper ratings are from HR to B

the correlation is turned to be positive when the ratings are A and AA.

the APR decrease with the increase of borrow term for people with HR-C raings. But for people with B-AA, the APR increase with the borrow term.

the states it's a quiet intersting
